    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-12-09T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-12-09T22:00:00-05:00" n="477"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d477">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751H.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1"
                    >MSP</gloss>/12–1053: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador at Saigon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Heath</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-12-10T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 10, 1953—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>997. For <persName corresp="#p_BPW1">Bonsal</persName>. Although I do not wish to
                    make final recommendations at this juncture, I invite your attention to <gloss
                        target="#t_Tousfo1">Tousfo</gloss> 587 December 7<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d477fn1">Not found in Department of State files.</note> setting
                    forth proposed <gloss target="#t_STEM1">STEM</gloss> programs for <gloss
                        target="#t_FOAW1">FOA/W</gloss> approval in respect of Cambodia.</p>
                <p>In present murky political atmosphere in Cambodia and given the King’s reimposed
                    self-exile, it is not possible to discern future trends of policy in that
                    Kingdom. However, such evidence as we have suggests that trend toward neutralism
                    is very strong. In my view, we should not give aid to Cambodia unless it is
                    willing to stand up and be counted in the fight against Communism.</p>
                <p>Although actual amount of our economic aid to Cambodia is not large, political
                    fact remains that Cambodians see unusual numbers of <pb facs="0949" n="917"
                        xml:id="pg_917"/>
                    <gloss target="#t_STEM1">STEM</gloss> personnel led by the enthusiastic
                        <persName>McReynolds</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d477fn2">Wilbur
                            <persName>McReynolds</persName>, Director of the Foreign Operations
                        Administration Mission in Indochina.</note> This gives them inevitable
                    impression that US Government is anxious to replace France as a principal
                    supplier of Cambodian needs and, unlike France, free of obligations on part of
                    Cambodia. Such a political atmosphere, particularly at time when Cambodian
                    Government should address itself to serious problem of negotiating final
                    independence with French Government, not conducive to furtherance of our policy
                    in Indochina.</p>
                <p>A further consideration is fact that, if Cambodians show irresponsible attitude
                    or present extreme demands on France, it will be difficult, if not impossible,
                    for Vietnamese and Laotians not to do likewise. In consequence, what Cambodia
                    does assumes disproportionate importance throughout remainder of Indochina.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Heath</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
